\v 6 \w They|strong="H1992"\w* \w will|strong="H3068"\w* \w go|strong="H3212"\w* \w to|strong="H3068"\w* \w seek|strong="H1245"\w* \w the|strong="H3068"\w* \w Lord|strong="H3068"\w* \w with|strong="H3068"\w* \w their|strong="H3068"\w* \w herds|strong="H1241"\w* \w and|strong="H3068"\w* \w flocks|strong="H6629"\w*,\f + \fr 5:6 \ft The mention of herds and flocks indicates that the people were using many sacrifices and offerings, thinking God would be pleased. However, theirs is not a true worship, but is more like pagan worship trying to appease the deity.\f* \w but|strong="H3808"\w* \w they|strong="H1992"\w* \w will|strong="H3068"\w* \w not|strong="H3808"\w* \w find|strong="H4672"\w* \w him|strong="H4672"\w*, \w for|strong="H3068"\w* \w he|strong="H3068"\w* \w has|strong="H3068"\w* given \w up|strong="H3212"\w* \w on|strong="H3068"\w* \w them|strong="H1992"\w*.  
\v 7 \w They|strong="H3588"\w* \w have|strong="H3068"\w* \w been|strong="H3068"\w* unfaithful \w to|strong="H3068"\w* \w the|strong="H3588"\w* \w Lord|strong="H3068"\w* \w and|strong="H1121"\w* \w have|strong="H3068"\w* \w had|strong="H3068"\w* \w children|strong="H1121"\w* \w that|strong="H3588"\w* \w are|strong="H1121"\w* \w not|strong="H3588"\w* \w his|strong="H3068"\w*.\f + \fr 5:7 \ft The word used here of the children is that they are “foreign”—meaning that they are both illegitimate and also the offspring of “foreign” gods.\f* \w Now|strong="H6258"\w* \w the|strong="H3588"\w* \w New|strong="H2320"\w* \w Moon|strong="H2320"\w* \w will|strong="H3068"\w* destroy \w them|strong="H1121"\w* \w along|strong="H3588"\w* \w with|strong="H3068"\w* \w their|strong="H3068"\w* fields.\f + \fr 5:7 \ft Various explanations of this sentence have been given. The observance of New Moon festivals was part of Israelite worship but had become corrupted (see for example \xt Isaiah 1:13\ft ), so this could be now taken as a symbol for pagan worship. In addition the northern kingdom under Jeroboam had instituted different festivals which were not ordained of God (see \xt 1 Kings 12:33\ft ). The main point is the corrupting influence of pagan beliefs on the genuine worship of the true God.\f*   
\p
