\v 1 \w Israel|strong="H3478"\w* \w is|strong="H2896"\w* \w like|strong="H3478"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* spreading\f + \fr 10:1 \ft The word used here usually means “to lay waste.” While many translations use terms such as “luxuriant,” the point made here is that this vine is unpruned and overgrown, and additionally only produces fruit “for itself”—not a good description of a productive vine for the gardener.\f* \w vine|strong="H1612"\w* \w that|strong="H3478"\w* \w produces|strong="H7737"\w* \w fruit|strong="H6529"\w* \w for|strong="H4196"\w* itself. \w The|strong="H3190"\w* \w more|strong="H7235"\w* \w fruit|strong="H6529"\w* \w they|strong="H3478"\w* produced, \w the|strong="H3190"\w* \w more|strong="H7235"\w* \w altars|strong="H4196"\w*\f + \fr 10:1 \ft Altars used for pagan worship.\f* \w they|strong="H3478"\w* built. \w The|strong="H3190"\w* \w more|strong="H7235"\w* \w productive|strong="H2896"\w* \w the|strong="H3190"\w* land, \w the|strong="H3190"\w* \w more|strong="H7235"\w* \w beautiful|strong="H2896"\w* \w they|strong="H3478"\w* \w made|strong="H7235"\w* \w the|strong="H3190"\w* sacred \w pillars|strong="H4676"\w*.\f + \fr 10:1 \ft Again, pagan symbols used for the worship of fertility gods.\f*  
\v 2 \w The|strong="H6258"\w* \w people|strong="H3820"\w* \w have|strong="H6258"\w* \w minds|strong="H3820"\w* \w that|strong="H1931"\w* \w are|strong="H3820"\w* deceptive, \w and|strong="H4196"\w* \w now|strong="H6258"\w* \w they|strong="H1931"\w* must \w take|strong="H2505"\w* responsibility \w for|strong="H4196"\w* \w their|strong="H7703"\w* guilt. \w The|strong="H6258"\w* Lord \w will|strong="H3820"\w* \w break|strong="H6202"\w* apart \w their|strong="H7703"\w* \w altars|strong="H4196"\w* \w and|strong="H4196"\w* \w destroy|strong="H7703"\w* \w their|strong="H7703"\w* sacred \w pillars|strong="H4676"\w*.  
\v 3 \w Then|strong="H6258"\w* \w they|strong="H3588"\w* \w will|strong="H3068"\w* say, “\w We|strong="H3588"\w* \w have|strong="H3068"\w* \w no|strong="H3808"\w* \w king|strong="H4428"\w*, \w for|strong="H3588"\w* \w we|strong="H3068"\w* \w do|strong="H6213"\w* \w not|strong="H3808"\w* \w fear|strong="H3372"\w* \w the|strong="H3588"\w* \w Lord|strong="H3068"\w*, \w and|strong="H3068"\w* \w yet|strong="H3588"\w* \w what|strong="H4100"\w* \w would|strong="H3068"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w king|strong="H4428"\w* \w do|strong="H6213"\w* \w for|strong="H3588"\w* \w us|strong="H6213"\w*?”  
\v 4 \w They|strong="H5921"\w* \w speak|strong="H1696"\w* \w empty|strong="H1285"\w* \w words|strong="H1697"\w*, swearing \w false|strong="H7723"\w* \w promises|strong="H1697"\w* \w to|strong="H1696"\w* \w make|strong="H3772"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w covenant|strong="H1285"\w*.\f + \fr 10:4 \ft The context is making false promises to God of agreements they do not intend to keep. \f* \w Their|strong="H5921"\w* “\w justice|strong="H4941"\w*” flourishes \w like|strong="H1697"\w* \w poisonous|strong="H7219"\w* \w weeds|strong="H7219"\w* \w in|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w furrows|strong="H8525"\w* \w of|strong="H1697"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* \w field|strong="H7704"\w*.  
\v 5 \w Those|strong="H4480"\w* \w who|strong="H5971"\w* \w live|strong="H1481"\w* \w in|strong="H5921"\w* \w Samaria|strong="H8111"\w* tremble \w in|strong="H5921"\w* \w awe|strong="H1481"\w* \w at|strong="H5921"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* \w calf|strong="H5697"\w* \w of|strong="H4480"\w* \w Beth-aven|strong="H1007"\w*.\f + \fr 10:5 \ft The real name of the place was Bethel, the house of God, but because of the pagan practices celebrated there the later prophets referred to it as Beth-aven, the house of nothingness (idols).\f* \w Its|strong="H5921"\w* \w people|strong="H5971"\w* \w mourn|strong="H5921"\w* \w for|strong="H3588"\w* \w it|strong="H5921"\w* \w in|strong="H5921"\w* \w their|strong="H5921"\w* pagan rituals, \w while|strong="H3588"\w* \w its|strong="H5921"\w* \w idolatrous|strong="H3649"\w* \w priests|strong="H3649"\w* celebrate \w its|strong="H5921"\w* \w glory|strong="H3519"\w*. \w But|strong="H3588"\w* \w it|strong="H5921"\w* \w will|strong="H5971"\w* \w certainly|strong="H3588"\w* \w be|strong="H5971"\w* \w taken|strong="H1540"\w* \w away|strong="H1540"\w* \w from|strong="H4480"\w* \w them|strong="H5921"\w*.\f + \fr 10:5 \ft The verbs used in this verse describe the pagan worship of Baal, in which his death is mourned with self-mutilation and then his return is celebrated with orgiastic rites. However, the idol will eventually be taken away by the Assyrians when they invade.\f* \w It|strong="H5921"\w* \w will|strong="H5971"\w* \w be|strong="H5971"\w* \w brought|strong="H1540"\w* \w to|strong="H5921"\w* Assyria \w as|strong="H3588"\w* tribute \w for|strong="H3588"\w* \w the|strong="H5921"\w* great \w king|strong="H5921"\w*.  
