\p
\v 4 \w Yet|strong="H3068"\w* \w I|strong="H3045"\w* \w am|strong="H3068"\w* \w the|strong="H3068"\w* \w Lord|strong="H3068"\w* \w your|strong="H3068"\w* \w God|strong="H3068"\w* \w who|strong="H3068"\w* \w brought|strong="H3467"\w* \w you|strong="H3045"\w* \w out|strong="H3045"\w* \w of|strong="H3068"\w* \w the|strong="H3068"\w* land \w of|strong="H3068"\w* \w Egypt|strong="H4714"\w*. \w You|strong="H3045"\w* \w shall|strong="H3068"\w* \w know|strong="H3045"\w*\f + \fr 13:4 \ft A variation of the Ten Commandments with “know” replacing “have” (\xt Exodus 20:3\ft ). This change is significant in that the word “know” carries overtones of intimate relations, and can be linked to the erotic nature of Baal worship. Israel should not be “knowing” Baal but the true God.\f* \w no|strong="H3808"\w* \w other|strong="H1115"\w* gods \w but|strong="H3808"\w* \w me|strong="H3467"\w*. \w None|strong="H3808"\w* \w can|strong="H3045"\w* \w save|strong="H3467"\w* \w you|strong="H3045"\w* \w except|strong="H2108"\w* \w me|strong="H3467"\w*.  
